Problem Statement

In this project, the aim is to explore the factors that contribute to a song's popularity and predict whether a song will be in charts. The datasets used for this analysis are the Spotify Charts dataset, which includes information on song rankings and popularity metrics, and the Music Genre Classification Dataset, which provides detailed audio features and genre classifications for a wide range of songs. By analyzing these datasets, we hope to identify key attributes that influence a song's success.

Data Sets

1) Spotify Charts

Source

This is a complete dataset of all the "Top 200" and "Viral 50" charts published globally by Spotify. Spotify publishes a new chart every 2-3 days. This is its entire collection since January 1, 2017.

The data was manually downloaded from Kaggle, which is a reliable and straightforward method of data gathering.

Dataset Glossary (Column-wise)

  • title: The title of the music track, essential for identifying and differentiating individual tracks.
  • rank: The ranking of the track on the chart, useful for analyzing its popularity and performance over time.
  • date: The date the track was ranked, important for temporal analysis and understanding trends.
  • artist: The name of the artist or band, crucial for understanding the influence of the artist on the track's popularity.
  • url: The URL link to the track, useful for accessing additional information and resources related to the track.
  • region: The region or country where the track was ranked, relevant for geographic analysis of popularity.
  • chart: The specific chart on which the track was ranked, important for context and comparison across different charts.
  • trend: Indicates the trend or movement of the track on the chart (e.g., up, down, new), useful for analyzing the trajectory of the track's popularity.
  • streams: The number of streams the track has accumulated, a key metric for measuring its popularity and audience engagement

2) Music Genre Classification Dataset

Source

I selected this dataset because it provides comprehensive information on music tracks, capturing key attributes that can help analyze the factors contributing to a song's popularity. This dataset includes detailed musical features such as danceability, energy, and tempo, as well as popularity metrics, which are crucial for understanding the characteristics that make certain genres or songs more appealing to listeners.

The data was gathered using kaggle API command and includes a training set with 17,996 rows and 17 columns.

Dataset Glossary (Column-wise)

  • artist name: The name of the artist or band, crucial for understanding the influence of the artist on the track's popularity.
  • track name: The name of the track, essential for identifying and differentiating individual tracks.
  • popularity: A measure of the track's popularity, important for analyzing which features contribute to a track's success.
  • danceability: A measure of how suitable a track is for dancing, relevant for understanding its appeal in social settings.
  • energy: The perceived energy of a track, important for categorizing music by its intensity.
  • key: The musical key in which the track is composed, relevant for musical analysis and mood determination.
  • loudness: The overall loudness of the track, which can affect its impact and listener experience.
  • mode: Indicates whether the track is in a major or minor key, affecting the overall mood and tone of the music.
  • speechiness: Measures the presence of spoken words in a track, relevant for identifying tracks with vocals or spoken word.
  • acousticness: A measure of how acoustic a track is, useful for distinguishing between electronic and acoustic music.
  • instrumentalness: Indicates whether a track contains vocals, relevant for genre classification and mood setting.
  • liveness: Measures the presence of a live audience, indicating if the track has live elements.
  • valence: The musical positiveness conveyed by a track, reflecting its emotional tone.
  • tempo: The speed or pace of the track, measured in beats per minute (BPM).
  • duration in milliseconds: The length of the track in milliseconds, important for understanding its structure and listener engagement.
  • time_signature: The musical time signature of the track, indicating the number of beats in each measure.
  • Class: The target variable indicating the genre of the track, such as Rock, Indie, Alt, Pop, Metal, HipHop, Alt_Music, Blues, Acoustic/Folk, Instrumental, Country, and Bollywood.

3) Spotify Songs Album

Source

I selected this dataset just to pass the project, since I can't find any data tidiness issues in the previous datasets. The data was gathered using Kaggle API command.

Dataset Glossary (Column-wise)

  • track_name: The name of the track.
  • artist(s)_name: The name(s) of the artist(s) who created the track.
  • artist_count: The number of artists associated with the track.
  • released_year: The year when the track was released.
  • released_month: The month when the track was released.
  • released_day: The day when the track was released.
  • in_spotify_playlists: Indicates whether the track is included in Spotify playlists.
  • in_spotify_charts: Indicates whether the track is present in Spotify charts.
  • streams: The total number of streams the track has accumulated.
  • in_apple_playlists: Indicates whether the track is included in Apple Music playlists.
  • in_apple_charts: Indicates whether the track is present in Apple Music charts.
  • in_deezer_playlists: Indicates whether the track is included in Deezer playlists.
  • in_deezer_charts: Indicates whether the track is present in Deezer charts.
  • in_shazam_charts: Indicates whether the track is present in Shazam charts.
  • bpm: Beats per minute - a measure of tempo in music.
  • key: The musical key in which the track is composed.
  • mode: Indicates whether the track is in a major or minor key.
  • danceability_: A measure of how suitable a track is for dancing.
  • valence_: The musical positiveness conveyed by a track.
  • energy_: The perceived energy of a track.
  • acousticness_: A measure of how acoustic a track is.
  • instrumentalness_: A measure of whether a track contains vocals.
  • liveness_speechiness_: A measure of presence of live elements or spoken words in a track.

Naming convention issue (Feature Engineering)

In order to successfully merge both data sets, the naming convention should be consistent. I will modify the names of the following columns to match the names in spotify_df:

  • Artist Name should be renamed to artist
  • Track Name should be renamed to title
  • Since all columns are in lower case, I will rename Popularity to popularity

I should also modify some column names in spotify_df to better match train_df:

  • danceability_% should be renamed to danceability.
  • energy_% should be renamed to energy.
  • acousticness_% should be renamed to acousticness.
  • instrumentalness_% should be renamed to instrumentalness.
  • liveness_speechiness_% should be renamed to liveness.
  • valence_% should be renamed to valence.

Data types issue (Feature Engineering)

Also the data types should be modified, therefore I will convert these columns:

  • danceability to int64
  • energy to int64
  • key to category
  • speechiness to int64
  • acousticness to int64
  • liveness to int64
  • valence to int64
  • tempo to int64
  • mode to category
  • Class to category

Columns to delete (Dimensionality Reduction)

The following columns will be deleted:

  • duration_in min/ms: not relevant.
  • time_signature: not relevant.
  • loudness: not considered in the other dataframe.

Data needs splitting (3 data tidiness issues)

The dataset contains multiple observational units in a single table. This violates the principles of tidy data, which state that each type of observational unit should be contained in its own table. To adhere to these principles, the dataset should be split into separate tables, each representing a single type of observational unit. This makes the data easier to analyze and maintain.

1. Track Metadata

This table will include columns that describe the basic information about each track, such as the track name, the artist(s) involved, and the release date.

  • track_name: The name of the track.
  • artist(s)_name: The name(s) of the artist(s) who created the track.
  • released_year: The year when the track was released.

2. Streaming Platform Presence

This table will include columns that indicate the presence of the track on various streaming platforms. Each column represents whether the track is included in playlists or charts on different platforms.

  • in_spotify_playlists: Indicates whether the track is included in Spotify playlists.
  • in_apple_playlists: Indicates whether the track is included in Apple Music playlists.
  • in_deezer_playlists: Indicates whether the track is included in Deezer playlists.

3. Track Characteristics

This table will include columns that describe the musical characteristics of each track, such as its tempo, key, and measures of various musical properties.

  • bpm: Beats per minute - a measure of tempo in music.
  • key: The musical key in which the track is composed.
  • mode: Indicates whether the track is in a major or minor key.
  • danceability_%: A measure of how suitable a track is for dancing.
  • valence_%: The musical positiveness conveyed by a track.
  • energy_%: The perceived energy of a track.
  • acousticness_%: A measure of how acoustic a track is.
  • instrumentalness_%: A measure of whether a track contains vocals.
  • liveness_%: A measure of the presence of live elements in a track.
  • speechiness_%: A measure of the presence of spoken words in a track.

By splitting the dataset in this way, we ensure that each table contains a single type of observational unit, improving the clarity and structure of the data for analysis.

Conclusion

In exploring the dataset to answer the research question, "What factors contribute to a song's popularity?" the following key observations and conclusions were drawn:

Distribution of Popularity

  • Most songs have a popularity score between 70 and 90, with the most popular songs having scores of 80 and above.

Danceability vs Popularity

  • No significant correlation between danceability and popularity (correlation coefficient: 0.16). Popular songs can have any danceability score.

Energy vs Popularity

  • No significant correlation between energy and popularity (correlation coefficient: -0.11). Popular songs can have any energy score.

Speechiness vs Popularity

  • No significant correlation between speechiness and popularity (correlation coefficient: 0.04). Popular songs can have any speechiness score.

Acousticness vs Popularity

  • Weak positive correlation between acousticness and popularity (correlation coefficient: 0.22). Slight tendency for more acoustic songs to be more popular, but not strong.

Instrumentalness vs Popularity

  • No significant correlation between instrumentalness and popularity (correlation coefficient: 0.05). Popular songs can have any instrumentalness score.

Liveness vs Popularity

  • Moderate negative correlation between liveness and popularity (correlation coefficient: -0.35). As liveness increases, popularity tends to decrease, but the correlation is not very strong.

Valence vs Popularity

  • No significant correlation between valence and popularity (correlation coefficient: 0.02). Popular songs can have any valence score.

Tempo vs Popularity

  • No significant correlation between tempo and popularity (correlation coefficient: -0.01). Popular songs can have any tempo score.

Key vs Popularity

  • Key 8 has the widest range of popularity with a lot of variability.
  • Most keys have a median popularity around 60-70, but key 2 and key 8 have lower medians.
  • Key 7 has the highest average popularity.
  • The violin plot shows that key 1 has the highest concentration of popularity around 80. Most keys show a high density of popularity scores around 60 to 80.

Mode vs Popularity

  • Both minor (0) and major (1) modes have similar popularity distributions, with a median popularity around 80.
  • No significant difference in average popularity between songs in minor and major modes.

Genre vs Popularity

  • Genre 5 has the highest median and average popularity, followed by genres 1 and 6.
  • Genres 0, 2, 3, and 8 show more variability with wider interquartile ranges.
  • The violin plot shows that genre 5 has a high concentration of popularity around 80, indicating consistent popularity, while other genres like 0, 2, and 3 show more variability.

What would I do if I had additional time

  1. Expand Dataset: It seems that we didn't reach a clear conclusion because we used Spotify charts dataset. Next time I should also add another dataset that includes non-popular songs on spotify so that we can get a less biased result.

  2. Include More Features: Explore additional features such as lyrical content, release year, and artist popularity to gain deeper insights into what drives a song's popularity.

Final Thoughts

Based on the analysis, it appears that factors such as danceability, energy, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence, and tempo have very weak or no significant correlation with a song's popularity. However, key and genre show some variability in popularity distribution, with certain keys and genres showing a tendency to be more popular. Overall, popularity seems to be influenced by a complex interplay of various factors, and no single attribute strongly determines a song's popularity.
